│ always evaluated, so poison exposure does not worsen (the original AND would  │
│ already propagate poison from either operand). However, when the AND          │
│ originates from a logical-select pattern (select cond, val, false)            │
│ short-circuit semantics apply: the second operand (%cmp) would not be         │
│ evaluated in the semantic sense if %ord is false, and more importantly,       │
│ poison in the non-selected arm does not propagate through a select. Folding   │
│ directly to a single fcmp drops the guarding 'ord' test and makes the poison  │
│ from fabs(x) observable. The code attempts to be poison-safe by passing       │
│ IsLogicalSelect to foldLogicOfFCmps, but the finite-test transform does not   │
│ check IsLogicalSelect and therefore incorrectly fires in this context.        │
│                                                                               │
│ Thus, missing poison-safety gating for the finite-test combine when operating │
│ on a logical-select derived boolean expression causes the miscompile.         │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit file llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp lines       │
│ 1483-1490.                                                                    │
│ Change the condition that triggers the finite test transform from:            │
│   if (IsAnd && stripSignOnlyFPOps(LHS0) == stripSignOnlyFPOps(RHS0)) {        │
│     ...                                                                       │
│   }                                                                           │
│ to include a guard against logical-select contexts:                           │
│   if (IsAnd && !IsLogicalSelect && stripSignOnlyFPOps(LHS0) ==                │
│ stripSignOnlyFPOps(RHS0)) {                                                   │
│     ...                                                                       │
│   }                                                                           │
│ Add a comment explaining why this restriction is necessary (short-circuit     │
│ select preserves poison in the non-taken arm; combining removes the guard and │
│ can expose poison).                                                           │
│ This prevents the unsafe transform while retaining canonicalization for true  │
│ bitwise AND expressions.                                                      │
│ Optionally, future work could attempt a more precise analysis (e.g., proving  │
│ RHS cannot be poison or inserting freeze), but the minimal safe fix is to     │
│ block the transform under IsLogicalSelect.                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By adding '!IsLogicalSelect' to the finite-test folding condition, we ensure  │
│ InstCombine does not collapse a select-based short-circuit pattern into a     │
│ single fcmp that exposes poison. This preserves original semantics for cases  │
│ where the second operand can be poison yet masked by the select, fixing the   │
│ miscompile demonstrated by the reproducer and Alive2 failure while leaving    │
│ other finite-test canonicalizations intact.                                   │
